  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two orbits of a spaceship around one planet. One is labeled Original Circular Orbit, and the other is labeled New Elliptical Orbit. The planet is to the left of the center of the New Elliptical Orbit. The orbits intersect at a point labeled P, which is where the spaceship changes from its original circular orbit to the new elliptical orbit. Two arrows are drawn from point P. One arrow points upward and to the right, and is tangent to the path of the elliptical orbit, and the other arrow points horizontally to the right, below the path of the elliptical orbit, and is tangent to the path of the circular orbit. A note indicates the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"/images/cf69aabef42c443da9288569e5174605.svg\"></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A spaceship orbits a distant planet in a circular orbit, as shown in the figure. When the spaceship reaches Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>, it momentarily fires its thrusters directly toward the center of the planet, causing the spaceship’s orbit to become elliptical. The two arrows in the figure represent the spaceship’s velocity at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> for the two orbits. Consider the angular momentum <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L sub ship\"><math alttext=\"L sub ship\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mtext>ship</mtext></msub></math></span></span> of the spaceship about the planet’s center and the total mechanical energy <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E sub system\"><math alttext=\"E sub system\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mtext>sys</mtext></msub></math></span></span> of the spaceship-planet system. Which of the following identifies the quantity that will be the same for both the original circular orbit and the new elliptical orbit and provides correct reasoning for the claim?</p>\n",
    "answer": "i1",
